      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/adduct-ion-parent-ion-pairing-analysis/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Metabolites typically form adducts with ions derived from inorganic salts or residual water, inherently present in all biological samples. The most common adducts are formed with H+, Na+, K+, or Cl\u2013... MALDI matrices tend to form abundant ion clusters of matrix molecules and occasionally were described as matrix adducts... we investigated the abundance of adducts across a broad spectrum of MALDI-MSI datasets... Our findings with mass2adduct, developed for adduct abundance estimation, highlight adduct formation of metabolites with known alkali metal ions and also matrix molecules.",
      "asbval:note": null,
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-0c04720",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "adduct-ion-parent-ion-pairing-analysis",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Apply this skill when adduct formation is suspected to obscure metabolite identity\u2014particularly in MALDI-MSI where matrix ions (e.g., DHB, CHCA) and sample salts (Na\u207a, K\u207a) readily form adducts with metabolites.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:20:58.759759+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/adduct-ion-parent-ion-pairing-analysis/007",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The typically thousands of measured signals in metabolomics experiments often remain unidentified and have been described as dark metabolome... Our results highlight that the dark metabolome of MALDI-MSI datasets might be not so dark after all, but merely clouded by the signals added through matrix adducts.",
      "asbval:note": null,
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-0c04720",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "adduct-ion-parent-ion-pairing-analysis",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Use it to recover 'dark metabolome' peaks that would otherwise be missed because they appear as distinct m/z values rather than as a single peak.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:20:58.759759+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/adduct-mass-difference-matching/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We compiled a set of matrix-related adducts into a list of adducts and mass differences for typical chemical transformations to match calculated \u0394mass values of a dataset (see Supporting Table S1). We used the list to identify the number of possible adducts based on specific m/z differences for each ion pair in a dataset. Our workflow is available as a software package for R, called mass2adduct.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms mass2adduct matches mass differences against a reference list of known adducts and identifies abundant adducts. However, the paper does not mention specific function names 'adductMatch()' or 'topAdducts()' \u2014 these function names cannot be verified from the passages provided. The core workflow (mass difference calculation, histogram binning, matching to known adducts) is confirmed.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-0c04720",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "adduct-mass-difference-matching",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "This skill matches observed mass differences from MS imaging data against a reference database of known molecular adducts (such as matrix or salt ions) to identify and rank abundant adduct species. It is applied after computing pairwise mass differences between all detected peaks",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:21:15.091502+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/adduct-mass-difference-matching/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Our workflow is available as a software package for R, called mass2adduct. It allows data import in various formats (e.g., imzML via Cardinal, intensity tables in CSV format), parallelization to speed up correlation testing, and several visualization tools.",
      "asbval:note": "mass2adduct is confirmed as an R package for adduct matching. However, specific function names 'adductMatch()' and 'topAdducts()' are not mentioned in the passages. The paper describes the workflow but does not expose individual function names.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-0c04720",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "adduct-mass-difference-matching",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "mass2adduct: R package providing adductMatch() and topAdducts() functions for matching histogram mass differences to known adducts",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
