    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/adduct-mass-difference-matching/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "It allows data import in various formats (e.g., imzML via Cardinal, intensity tables in CSV format)",
      "asbval:note": "Cardinal is confirmed as a tool for data preprocessing and import into mass2adduct. The paper also states: 'Peak lists and intensity matrices for datasets #1\u20133, #5\u20137, #9, #13\u201316, #19, and #20 were generated with SCiLS v2019b (Bruker, Germany)' and 'Datasets #4, #8, #10, #17, and #18 were binned with Cardinal MSI v2 at a bin width of 1 mDa.' Cardinal is used for preprocessing.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-0c04720",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "adduct-mass-difference-matching",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Cardinal: Optional upstream tool for preprocessing and peak-binning MSI data before conversion to msimat format for mass2adduct",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:21:15.091502+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/adduct-mass-difference-matching/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "A common method to find adducts is the matching of mass differences between a parent ion and higher m/z values. By leveraging high mass resolution and high mass accuracy data, ideally below 5 ppm, the accuracy of detecting specific and common mass difference is higher. We applied this idea to high-mass-resolution MSI data collected in positive ionization mode by first calculating mass differences (\u0394mass) between all pairs of detected peaks in a MALDI-MSI dataset from a mouse brain tissue section (dataset #10) and then creating a histogram of all \u0394mass (see Figure 1A).",
      "asbval:note": null,
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-0c04720",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "adduct-mass-difference-matching",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Apply this skill when you have computed a histogram of pairwise mass differences from MS imaging data and need to (1) identify which observed mass differences correspond to biologically relevant or chemically known adducts, or (2) rank the most frequently observed mass difference",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:21:15.091502+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/adduct-mass-difference-matching/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The input data needs to be generated with high mass accuracy (below 5 ppm) to allow for an accurate and reliable detection of \u0394mass for ion pairs. Detection of peaks in each single mass spectrum of an MSI dataset is a challenging task, and rigorous care should be taken to perform this step as accurate as possible.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper confirms that mass2adduct operates on preprocessed, peak-detected MSI data with high mass accuracy. However, the specific function name 'massdiff()' is not mentioned in the passages; the paper refers to 'calculating mass differences (\u0394mass)' but does not name a specific function.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-0c04720",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "adduct-mass-difference-matching",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "This is typical after baseline-corrected, peak-binned MSI data has been loaded and massdiff() has been applied.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:21:15.091502+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/cardinal-imaging-object-conversion/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Datasets #4, #8, #10, #17, and #18 were binned with Cardinal MSI v2 at a bin width of 1 mDa, and further processing included a 1% frequency filter (default setting) and a threshold of 0.05% top peak intensity. ... The input data needs to be generated with high mass accuracy (below 5 ppm) to allow for an accurate and reliable detection of \u0394mass for ion pairs. ... MSI data in imzML format or intensity matrices in CSV format can be imported to mass2adduct.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms Cardinal v2 preprocessing and mass2adduct input formats (imzML via Cardinal, CSV intensity tables), but does NOT explicitly name or document a 'cardinal2msimat()' function or 'msimat' format. The paper states mass2adduct accepts 'imzML format or intensity matrices in CSV format' \u2014 no intermediate 'msimat' object type is mentioned. The card appears to invent a conversion function and format name not present in the paper.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-0c04720",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "cardinal-imaging-object-conversion",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Convert Cardinal MSI data objects (MSProcessedImagingExperiment or MSContinuousImagingExperiment) to mass2adduct's msimat format to enable downstream adduct detection and spatial correlation analysis.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:21:31.913655+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/cardinal-imaging-object-conversion/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "MSI data in imzML format or intensity matrices in CSV format can be imported to mass2adduct. ... Datasets #4, #8, #10, #17, and #18 were binned with Cardinal MSI v2 at a bin width of 1 mDa",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms Cardinal v2 preprocessing and mass2adduct's ability to consume imzML and CSV formats, but does not document a dedicated 'msimat' format or 'cardinal2msimat()' conversion function. The card's scope conflates Cardinal's output (imzML or CSV) with a hypothetical intermediate 'msimat' format.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-0c04720",
