    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mass-spectrometry-imaging-data-interpretation/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Our approach is based on two major steps, calculating \u0394mass values between all peaks of a dataset and testing for spatial correlation only between parent and putative adduct ions... We compiled a set of matrix-related adducts into a list of adducts and mass differences for typical chemical transformations to match calculated \u0394mass values of a dataset... calculating individual correlation values between the intensities of a peak and its putative adduct peak across all pixels of a MALDI-MSI dataset provides statistical support for MS1-based adduct identifications",
      "asbval:note": "The paper describes a workflow for identifying adducts (including Na+ adducts) via mass difference calculation and spatial correlation testing. However, the research question specifically emphasizes 'sodium adduct ions' as the primary focus, while the paper's actual scope is broader\u2014it addresses Na+, K+, Cl\u2212, and especially matrix adducts (DHB, CHCA). The visualization claim ('color-coded scatter plots') is not explicitly described in the passages; the paper mentions 'visualization tools' and ion maps but does not detail scatter plot overlays. The workflow is confirmed but the specificity to sodium adducts alone is overstated.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-0c04720",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mass-spectrometry-imaging-data-interpretation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "A workflow for identifying and visualizing sodium adduct ions relative to their parent ions in MALDI-MSI data by computing pairwise mass differences, matching them to known adducts, testing spatial correlation, and overlaying adduct and parent peaks on mass spectra with color-cod",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:22:31.020438+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mass-spectrometry-imaging-data-interpretation/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Our workflow is available as a software package for R, called mass2adduct. It allows data import in various formats (e.g., imzML via Cardinal, intensity tables in CSV format), parallelization to speed up correlation testing, and several visualization tools... Software to perform the adduct identification and correlation testing are implemented in an R package, mass2adduct. The software and installation instructions are available on GitHub at https://github.com/kbseah/mass2adduct",
      "asbval:note": "mass2adduct is explicitly named and described as the primary R package for adduct identification and spatial correlation testing.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-0c04720",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mass-spectrometry-imaging-data-interpretation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "mass2adduct",
