    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mass-spectrometry-imaging-data-interpretation/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": null,
      "asbval:note": "The passages confirm that mass2adduct performs data import, pairwise mass difference calculation, adduct matching against a known list, spatial correlation testing, and visualization. However, the specific function names (msimat, massdiff, adductMatch, topAdducts, corrPairsMSI, corrPairsMSIchunks, pointsAdducts) are not mentioned in any of the provided passages. The paper describes the workflow conceptually but does not document the API. Insufficient information to verify function names.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-0c04720",
      "asbval:supported_raw": null,
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mass-spectrometry-imaging-data-interpretation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools[mass2adduct].role",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Provides the complete toolkit: msimat() for data import, massdiff() for pairwise difference computation, adductMatch() and topAdducts() for adduct identification, corrPairsMSI()/corrPairsMSIchunks() for spatial correlation testing, and pointsAdducts() for visualization overlay.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000302"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:22:31.020438+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000341"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mass-spectrometry-imaging-data-interpretation/007",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "we aimed to develop a method that enables automatic and unbiased detection of abundant adducts in MSI data... Adducts are expected to co-occur in the same spot as their parent metabolite for any given tissue sample... Our results suggest that including metabolite\u2013matrix adducts into database annotations can reduce the number of unannotated peaks and, on the other hand, will prevent possible false annotations and biological misinterpretations.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper confirms the use case of identifying whether peaks are adducts rather than distinct metabolites. However, the specific data format 'msimat' is not mentioned in the passages; the paper refers to 'imzML format' and 'CSV intensity tables' as input formats. The format name cannot be verified.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-0c04720",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mass-spectrometry-imaging-data-interpretation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "When you have preprocessed MALDI-MSI data (in msimat format) and want to determine whether abundant peaks are actually molecular adducts of simpler parent ions rather than distinct metabolites.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:22:31.020438+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mass-spectrometry-imaging-data-interpretation/008",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "A positive correlation value alone does not guarantee that two ions are chemically related. However, in combination with our prior knowledge on sample and matrix composition, it provides additional confidence to screen for potential adducts... We extended our correlation analysis to every proposed adduct pair within a dataset, which enabled us to remove false positives.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper explicitly describes using spatial correlation patterns to filter false positives and validate adduct identifications.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-0c04720",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mass-spectrometry-imaging-data-interpretation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Apply this skill when visual inspection alone cannot distinguish overlapping adduct and parent peaks, or when you need to filter false positive identifications by leveraging spatial co-localization patterns across pixels.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:22:31.020438+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mass-spectrometry-peak-pair-analysis/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "A common method to find adducts is the matching of mass differences between a parent ion and higher m/z values... We applied this idea to high-mass-resolution MSI data collected in positive ionization mode by first calculating mass differences (\u0394mass) between all pairs of detected peaks in a MALDI-MSI dataset from a mouse brain tissue section (dataset #10) and then creating a histogram of all \u0394mass... The mass difference was calculated for all pairs of peaks, and matched against a list of known adduct types",
      "asbval:note": "Core methodology directly described in paper.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-0c04720",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mass-spectrometry-peak-pair-analysis",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Identify and rank molecular adducts in mass spectrometry imaging by computing pairwise mass differences between all detected peaks, binning them into a histogram, and matching observed differences to known chemical species.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:22:52.850003+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mass-spectrometry-peak-pair-analysis/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Software to perform the adduct identification and correlation testing are implemented in an R package, mass2adduct. The software and installation instructions are available on GitHub at https://github.com/kbseah/mass2adduct",
      "asbval:note": "mass2adduct is confirmed as the core R package for adduct identification and correlation testing. However, the specific function names (massdiff, adductMatch, topAdducts, corrPairsMSI, corrPairsMSIchunks, msimat, diffGetPeaks) are not explicitly listed in the passages. The paper describes the workflow and capabilities but does not enumerate these specific function names.",
