    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/multiple-testing-correction-bonferroni/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "For each dataset, Pearson's two-sided correlation test was performed for all ion pairs using per-pixel intensity values. We applied three different methods to screen for false positives: (1) The Bonferroni correction was applied to the p-values from the correlation test, and pairs with corrected p \u2265 0.05 were rejected",
      "asbval:note": "The paper applies Bonferroni correction to p-values from Pearson correlation tests across all ion pairs, exactly matching the scope description.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-0c04720",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "multiple-testing-correction-bonferroni",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Apply Bonferroni correction when you have computed raw p-values for multiple independent statistical tests and need to report which results remain significant after accounting for multiple comparisons.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:24:04.550810+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/multiple-testing-correction-bonferroni/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "For each dataset, possible parent\u2013adduct ion pairs were identified in the following way: The mass difference was calculated for all pairs of peaks",
      "asbval:note": "The paper applies Bonferroni to thousands of pairwise ion comparisons in MSI datasets, but does not explicitly discuss the appropriateness of Bonferroni for 'moderate' test counts or acknowledge its conservative nature. The paper does apply it to large-scale testing (all peak pairs), which is consistent with the use case, but the scope's guidance about when Bonferroni is 'appropriate' is not directly supported.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-0c04720",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "multiple-testing-correction-bonferroni",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Bonferroni is appropriate when the number of tests is moderate (hundreds to low thousands) and you can afford conservative significance thresholds.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:24:04.550810+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/multiple-testing-correction-bonferroni/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Although changes in local sodium or potassium concentrations can impede strong correlations,16 an effect similar to strong local ion suppression occurs. The correlation values can be influenced by very low abundant ion pairs41 or the presence of isobaric metabolites with overlapping monoisotopic distribution patterns.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper acknowledges that ion pairs can be correlated and that this affects correlation analysis, but does not explicitly discuss the limitation of Bonferroni correction under non-independence. The paper does mention using alternative methods (FDR-based analysis) alongside Bonferroni, suggesting awareness of its limitations, but does not state that Bonferroni is inappropriate for correlated tests.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-0c04720",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "multiple-testing-correction-bonferroni",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "When NOT to use: test results are not independent (e.g., correlated ion pairs)\u2014Bonferroni assumes independence and will be too stringent under positive correlation.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:24:04.550810+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/sodium-adduct-detection-and-classification/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We found high counts of \u0394mass of 21.985 and 37.955 Da, which matched the \u0394mass between [M + H]+ and [M + Na]+ or [M + K]+, respectively... Adducts are expected to co-occur in the same spot as their parent metabolite for any given tissue sample. Consequently, calculating individual correlation values between the intensities of a peak and its putative adduct peak across all pixels of a MALDI-MSI dataset provides statistical support for MS1-based adduct identifications",
      "asbval:note": "Core methodology confirmed: mass difference matching for Na+ adducts (\u0394mass 21.985 Da) and spatial correlation filtering for false-positive removal.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-0c04720",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "sodium-adduct-detection-and-classification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Identify and visually distinguish sodium adduct ions ([M+Na]+) from their parent metabolite ions in MALDI-MSI data by matching observed mass differences to known sodium adduct masses, then spatially correlating parent\u2013adduct pairs to filter out false positives.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:24:20.295920+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/sodium-adduct-detection-and-classification/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Currently, there is a gap in transforming the measured m/z values to knowledge... The typically thousands of measured signals in metabolomics experiments often remain unidentified and have been described as dark metabolome... We propose to include matrix adducts into annotation processes to improve ion identifications in spatial metabolomics datasets to reduce the high percentage of previously unannotated m/z values",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly frames adduct detection as a method to illuminate the dark metabolome by recovering hidden metabolite identities.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-0c04720",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "sodium-adduct-detection-and-classification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "This skill enables interrogation of the 'dark metabolome'\u2014metabolites hidden as salt adducts in imaging datasets.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:24:20.295920+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/sodium-adduct-detection-and-classification/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Software to perform the adduct identification and correlation testing are implemented in an R package, mass2adduct. The software and installation instructions are available on GitHub at https://github.com/kbseah/mass2adduct",
      "asbval:note": "mass2adduct is confirmed as the core R package for adduct detection and correlation testing. However, the specific function names (massdiff, hist, adductMatch, topAdducts, diffGetPeaks, corrPairsMSI, corrPairsMSIchunks, pointsAdducts) are not explicitly listed in the passages. The paper describes the workflow (mass difference calculation, histogram matching, spatial correlation) but does not enumerate individual function names.",
